\section{Abstract}



\section{Introduction}

Contemporary global climate change is predicted to impact global hydrological cycling, threatening human communities and infrastructure situated around river corridors \parencite[e.g.][]{dankers_climate_2008}.
A key part of understanding the modern hazard posed by rapidly changing hydrological cycling is interpreting the geologic record of paleoclimate change and inferring landscape responses in fluvial environments.
Since climate is a key control on the flux of solutes and sediment from terrestrial environments to marine basins on continental margins, both the stratigraphic arrangement of sediments and abundance of biogeochemical proxies hosted in these sediments can be used to reconstruct paleoenvironmental change \parencite[e.g.][]{zachos_early_2008, emiliani_pleistocene_1955}.
However, stochastic sediment transport processes distort and modify the signal of changing climate conditions as it propagates through terrestrial environments to marine basins, precluding a straightforward interpretation of past climate in the stratigraphic record \parencite{foreman_autogenic_2017, romans_environmental_2016, armitage_transformation_2011}.
A detailed accounting of the mechanisms by which climate alters sediment production, transport, and deposition in terrestrial environments is therefore critical for reconstructing basin filling histories during periods of rapid climate change.

The Paleocene Eocene Thermal Maximum (PETM) is the most severe climate perturbation known in the Cenozoic Era \parencite{zachos_early_2008, slotnick_large_2012}.
Associated with altered hydrological cycling and precipitation extremes driven by rapid warming and accumulation of atmospheric carbon \parencite{carmichael_hydrological_2017}, the PETM serves as the best-studied analogue for contemporary climate warming \parencite{mcinerney_paleocene-eocene_2011}.
Globally, the PETM is identified by a negative excursion in carbon isotopes \parencite{kennett_abrupt_1991}, and is often associated with drastic changes in sedimentology.
In marginal marine environments, the PETM is most commonly associated with increased deposition of terrigenous clay \parencite{john_north_2008, stassen_perturbation_2012}, whereas in terrestrial environments, it is associated with coarsening of alluvial strata \parencite[e.g.][]{schmitz_abrupt_2007, pujalte_massive_2015, foreman_climate-driven_2014}.

In many localities, changes in paleodischarge and sediment flux have been invoked to explain sedimentological differences during the PETM.
Elevated water and sediment fluxes are interpreted to have caused coarse sediment progradation into alluvial basins, and increased fine sediment deposition in offshore environments \parencite{chen_estimating_2018, foreman_fluvial_2012}.
These studies argue that the hydrological and sedimentological shifts during the PETM should be recorded as changes in river channel geometries like width, depth, and slope.
However, the paleohydraulic techniques used to reconstruct these fluxes carry significant uncertainty \parencite[e.g.][]{trampush_empirical_2014}, and competing scenarios are also plausible given the same data.
It is particularly unclear whether water and sediment flux increased wholesale or whether precipitation became highly monsoonal, and sedimentological changes are driven by seasonally intense runoff \parencite{plink-bjorklund_morphodynamics_2015}.
These differing scenarios of terrestrial landscape response to the PETM each carry strong implications for interpreting sediment dispersal patterns and biogeochemical proxy data ultimately recorded in marine basins \parencite{foreman_autogenic_2017, trampush_identifying_2017, straub_influence_2013}.

In this study, we revisit the well-studied Piceance Basin (Colorado, USA), where changes in channel stacking patterns and sand enrichment have been attributed to increased water and sediment fluxes due to altered hydrological cycling during the PETM \parencite{foreman_fluvial_2012}.
New paleohydraulic techniques are used in conjunction with additional measurements of channel geometries to assess changes to fluvial dynamics during the PETM.
These field data are combined with insights from a geometric numerical model \parencite{chamberlin_using_2019} to analyze the impact of altered fluvial dynamics on sediment dispersal during the PETM in the Piceance Basin.

\section{Study Locality and Paleohydraulic Methods}

To study the impacts of PETM-modulated changes in hydrological cycling on fluvial systems, we turn to the Piceance Basin (Colorado, USA), an intermontane Laramide depocenter active throughout the Paleogene and Eocene \parencite{johnson_history_2003}.
Sedimentary fill of the Piceance Basin is conformable across the Paleocene-Eocene boundary, and the PETM interval is marked in the Piceance Basin by a distinctive \del{13}{C}{} isotope excursion, correlating with a distinctive sand-rich unit known as the Molina member of the Wasatch Formation \parencite{foreman_fluvial_2012}.

Juxtaposed between mud-rich units, sedimentological characteristics of the sandy Molina member contrast starkly with the underlying Atwell Gulch and the overlying Shire members of the Wasatch Formation \parencite{donnell_paleocene_1969}.
While the Atwell Gulch and Shire members largely consist of a matrix of muddy floodplain paleosols containing isolated channel sand bodies, the Molina member comprises interconnected, sheetlike amalgamated sand bodies with relatively thin intervening layers of floodplain mud.

While tectonic factors could have driven sand enrichment in the Molina member, detrital zircon analysis and basin-scale deposit geometries in the Wasatch Formation argue against a wholesale increase in sediment supply due to increased uplift rates or unroofing of sand-rich units in the hinterland \parencite{foreman_fluvial_2012}.
Additionally, the great distance of the paleo-shoreline ($>1000$ km) and a lack of evidence for temporally-variable subsidence indicate that a change in accommodation is unlikely to have influenced sedimentation in the Piceance Basin \parencite{johnson_history_2003}.

In their study, \textcite{foreman_fluvial_2012} indicate that the distinctive changes in channel stacking patterns and sand enrichment in the Molina member are best explained as a fluvial response to climate-induced changes in hydrological cycling during the PETM.
In particular, their data indicate that Piceance Basin rivers deepened and widened to convey more intense flows during the PETM, and further suggest that changing precipitation evacuated sediment from hillslopes, driving high fluxes during the PETM.
However, data on changing fluvial geometries like depth and slope from other basins are more equivocal with regard to both paleo-discharge and sediment flux \parencite[e.g.][]{chen_estimating_2018}.

Part of the source of this discrepancy is that paleohydraulic inversion techniques based on fluvial geometries carry substantial uncertainty \parencite{trampush_empirical_2014}.
Additional information can be gained by combining geometry-based methods with techniques to evaluate fluvial kinematics.
For example, work by \textcite{jones_characterizing_2007} suggests that the predominant avulsion style in an alluvial basin may be a characteristic of the channel-floodplain system, and \textcite{chamberlin_using_2019} indicate that reworking of fluvial bar structures can indicate the relative rate of fluvial reworking in the floodplain.
In this study, we evaluate the impact of the PETM on fluvial systems in the Piceance Basin by quantifying four key paleohydraulic parameters in the Piceance Basin: (1) channel flow depth, (2) fluvial slope, (3) lateral migration, and (4) avulsion style.

Paleohydraulic data were collected during three field campaigns from 2017-2019 as well as aggregated from previous literature and unpublished data.
Changes in paleo-flow depth through the Wasatch Formation by measuring the relief on fully-preserved fluvial barforms \parencite{ethridge_reconstructing_1977, mohrig_interpreting_2000}.
These paleo-flow depths were combined with co-located measurements of median bedload grain size interpreted using a hand lens and grain-size card to estimate paleoslope via the empirical scaling introduced by \textcite{trampush_empirical_2014}.
To estimate barform preservation, and relative floodplain reworking, drone imagery was collected for 12 outcrops in the Piceance Basin, and photogrammetry was used to construct 3D digital models of the outcrop surface.
Bar clinoforms were mapped on the 3D digital outcrops, and barforms were classified as either fully preserved, partially preserved, or truncated after \textcite{chamberlin_using_2019}.
Avulsion style was classified from field observations in all three members of the Wasatch formation using criteria in \textcite{jones_characterizing_2007}.

\section{Results}

Our new dataset of paleoflow depth, which includes literature values, indicates that paleoflow depths are statistically indistinguishable throughout the Wasatch Formation at a 95\% confidence level, as shown in Table \ref{tab:paleo_geom} and Figure \ref{fig:paleo_geom}a.
Additionally, our estimates of paleoslope in the Piceance Basin indicate no difference between the Molina member and the bounding members at a 95\% confidence level (Figure \ref{fig:paleo_geom}b).
This demonstrates that within the resolution of current paleohydraulic methods, rivers were likely not substantially deeper or steeper during the PETM as opposed to before or after.

However, mapping sedimentary structure preservation throughout the Wasatch Formation shows that barforms in the Molina member crosscut each other more frequently, and are less well preserved than in either the Shire or Atwell Gulch members.
In the Molina member, only \Sexpr{signif(pres$meanPres[2], digits = 3)}\% of barforms were fully preserved, whereas in the Atwell Gulch and Shire members, \Sexpr{signif(pres$meanPres[1], digits = 3)}\% and \Sexpr{signif(pres$meanPres[3], digits = 3)}\% of barforms were fully preserved, respectively (Figure \ref{fig:paleo_geom}c).
Using a $\chi^2$ test, we find that there are significantly fewer preserved barforms in the Molina member ($\chi^2$(\Sexpr{barpres_test$parameter},~n~=~\Sexpr{sum(barpres_test$observed)})~=~\Sexpr{signif(barpres_test$statistic, digits = 3)}, $\Sexpr{p_comp_reworking}$ (2-tailed)).
