\section{Discussion}

When river channels migrate and avulse, they simultaneously deposit sediment and also scour into shallow floodplain deposits, truncating young strata.
To first order, the stratigraphic architecture of floodplain deposits is controlled by the balance of channel kinematic rates against the background rates of sediment supply and accommodation creation.
All else being equal in alluvial strata, a preponderance of poorly preserved or truncated bars indicates that accommodation was not generated fast enough to subside floodplain deposits below the fluvial reworking depth \parencite{chamberlin_using_2019}.
Our estimates of bar preservation in the Piceance Basin therefore suggest that during Molina time (i.e. the PETM), river channels revisited locations frequently, cross-cutting previously deposited structures and reworking the floodplain surface to a greater degree than during Atwell Gulch or Shire time.
Since previous work indicates that base level change and tectonically-modulated subsidence are unlikely to have driven decreased accommodation during the PETM, the most parsimonious explanation for elevated reworking is that fluvial kinematic rates accelerated during Molina time.

Elevated water and sediment fluxes have previously been invoked to explain the increase in lateral migration and avulsion \parencite{foreman_fluvial_2012}, as would be expected from experimental studies \parencite{strong_mass-balance_2005, bryant_experimental_1995}.
However, the lack of detectable change in either channel depths or slopes in this study of the Piceance Basin argues against an overall increase in total water or sediment flux during the PETM.
In fact, recent paleosol records from both the Piceance Basin as well as the nearby Bighorn Basin suggest, instead, that during the PETM, these basins experienced either no change or a mild decrease in mean annual precipitation \parencite{kraus_transient_2007, lesko_increased_2019}.
This general finding is in agreement with climate models evaluated for PETM-like conditions, which generally predict overall drying conditions across the American Mountain West as a result of global warming \parencite{carmichael_hydrological_2017}.

While the PETM is associated with overall drying in the Piceance Basin, models and paleosol records also suggest that warming may have driven increases in precipitation seasonality.
Precipitation seasonality has been proposed as a strong control on channel dynamics both in modern system studies \parencite{fielding_role_2018, leier_mountains_2005} and in the rock record \parencite{plink-bjorklund_morphodynamics_2015}, but the mechanisms linking the two remain unclear.
Changes in floodplain vegetation due to seasonal aridity have been invoked both in the Piceance Basin and in other PETM stratigraphic sections to explain increased fluvial activity \parencite{foreman_fluvial_2012, wing_plant_2013}.
However, experimental results demonstrate that increased lateral mobility of channels can occur in the absence of vegetation, with only a change in discharge variability \parencite{esposito_sediment_2018}.

\textcite{esposito_sediment_2018} showed that introducing intense energetic flooding causes channels to migrate more rapidly and avulse more often such that channels frequently revisited locations on the floodplain.
In the experiments, accelerated lateral mobility is a consequence of weakened banks and crevassing, promoting river scour into previous deposits and aggradation of channel deposits, with the net effect that channel facies compose a greater fraction of the preserved stratigraphy.
These findings parallel our observations in the Piceance Basin, where we interpret elevated fluvial reworking in the Molina member and a switch from abrupt to transitional avulsions; both indicative of a change in fluvial dynamics.
The preponderance of channel deposits and truncated barforms during Molina time indicates that fluvial systems likely experienced accelerated channel migration, which drove heavy reworking of the shallow stratigraphy.
Since fluvial channel deposits primarily consist of sand, when rivers incise into floodplains and re\"entrain mud and silt overbank deposits, they replace fine overbank facies with coarse channel facies.
Additionally, the switch from abrupt to transitional avulsions during Molina time suggests that river banks were likely either weak and uncohesive or heavily dissected by crevasse channels, allowing coarse sediment to escape from the river during floods \parencite{jones_characterizing_2007}.

We therefore interpret that a climatically-modulated shift to highly seasonal precipitation during the PETM led to an increase in lateral mobility together with a shift to a transitional avulsion style, the effect of which was to preferentially partition sandy sediment to the floodplain, and enriching the strata with sand.
As a corollary, the reworking of mud and silt overbank deposits would have re\"entrained this sediment, and flushed it downstream to more distal basins.
In contrast, before and after the PETM, fine sediment was preferentially sequestered in floodplain deposits implying channels had strong, stable banks that confined flow and acted as conduits to flush sandy sediment downstream.

Studies of the PETM on continental margins commonly find that the interval is associated with elevated fluxes of terrigenous mud, \parencite{slotnick_large_2012, gibson_stratigraphic_2000} and which is often attributed to elevated sediment flux on continents overall during the PETM: a so-called ``global system-clearing'' event \parencite{foreman_fluvial_2012, jerolmack_shredding_2010}.
However, in their experiments, \textcite{esposito_sediment_2018} did not change the total water and sediment flux to the system, and yet still observed amalgamation of channel facies in the proximal floodplain environment.
This incongruity invites an alternative scenario, where elevated mud fluxes in distal basins like continental margins are not the result of increased overall flux, but rather a consequence of a morphodynamic ``distilling'' process.
Driven by highly seasonal precipitation, fluvial kinematics accelerated during the PETM, preferentially partitioning coarse sediment into floodplain deposits, whereas fine silt and mud was remobilized and bypassed to downstream basins.

This model is borne out in basin-wide estimates of sediment thickness, which indicate that whereas before and after the PETM, the Wasach Formation consists of approximately \mnote[20\%]{check} coarse material, during the PETM far more sand (up to \mnote[40\%]{check}) constitutes the strata.
While there is expected to be substantial regional heterogeneity in climatic forcing during the PETM, most studies in continental basins shows that a preponderance observe coarsening in alluvial strata \parencite[][]{pujalte_massive_2015, schmitz_abrupt_2007, foreman_fluvial_2012}.
This study from the Piceance Basin therefore serves as an example of a general trend that rapid climate warming may serve to drive the fluvial response by increasing the seasonality of regional precipitation, acclerating lateral migration and avulsion processes.

