\section{Conclusions and Implications}

In this study, paleohydraulic techniques were applied in the Piceance Basin of western Colorado to better constrain changes in channel-floodplain processes connected with abrupt climate perturbation during the PETM.
These new data indicate that while fluvial geometries like depth and slope are consistent across the PETM boundary, fluvial structures are more often truncated and cross-cut during the PETM interval, and avulsions become transitional in nature.
Taken together with experimental studies and new records of paleosol chemistry, these findings suggest that sedimentological shifts during the PETM in the Piceance Basin are not driven by overall increases in water and sediment flux, but rather by accelerated channel migration and a shift in avulsion style.

The Piceance Basin serves as an example that all else being equal, terrestrial floodplains subjected to seasonally intense precipitation will experience accelerated channel dynamics, allowing rivers to rework the floodplain and enrich the shallow stratigraphy in sand.
As a corollary, when rivers rework the surface during this ``morphodynamic distilling'' process, they re\"excavate mud and silt, and bypass it to downstream basins.
In contrast, channels in alluvial basins with low discharge variability can act as conduits for sand to bypass terrestrial floodplains and be deposited on shorelines and in marine basins.
This framework is advanced as an alternative to the ``global system-clearing event'' model of PETM landscape response, emphasizing that shifting hydrological regimes under global warming need not invoke transiently high sediment fluxes, but rather may simply re-apportion sediment through preferential partitioning.

